ne", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.998791515827179, "span": {"begin": 575, "end": 588}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "QB", "obj": "DNA", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 605, "end": 607}}, {"id": ["mesh:D006859"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hydrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995517134666443, "span": {"begin": 631, "end": 639}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000596"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "amino acid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995883703231812, "span": {"begin": 660, "end": 670}}, {"id": ["mesh:D012694"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Serine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9976100921630859, "span": {"begin": 697, "end": 703}}, {"id": ["mesh:D006639"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Histidine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9945740103721619, "span": {"begin": 712, "end": 721}}, {"id": ["mesh:C004532"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "quinone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9996832609176636, "span": {"begin": 820, "end": 827}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "QA", "obj": "DNA", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 883, "end": 885}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "QB", "obj": "DNA", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 889, "end": 891}}], "text": "This Key Event describes the competitive displacement of the endogenous electron carrier plastoquinone B (QB) from its binding site in the D1 protein (encoded by psbA) by an exogenous stressor, typically a Photosystem II (PSII) inhibitor.&nbsp;Under normal conditions, a plastoquinone molecule enters the QB site, accepts two electrons from the primary quinone QA and two protons from the stroma, becomes plastoquinol&nbsp;PQH2, and then leaves the site to continue the electron transport chain.&nbsp;Stressor molecules share structural similarities with the quinone ring of plastoquinone. They enter the QB pocket and form stable hydrogen bonds with specific amino acid residues, most critically Serine 264 and Histidine 215.&nbsp;Because the stressor binds with higher affinity or slower dissociation than the natural quinone. This physically blocks the transfer of electrons from QA to QB, and thus reduced photosynthetic efficiency..", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 22:01:56 +0000 2026"}